Rental revenue growth, FY26 capex/FCF guidance - In-line - Largely unchanged- We expect group rental revenue growth of \(c.2\%\) , in line with the May exit rate.- We see upside to FY26 FCF guidance, driven by the OBBBA.

> results at 7am UKt on Wednesday 3rd September. Analyst conference call at 11.30am UKt, dial in +44 (0) 33 0551 0200 with passcode: Ashtead Group Q1.

1Q26 (May- July): We expect group rental revenue growth of \(c.2\%\) at the midpoint of management's FY26 guidance of \(0.4\%\) and in line with the May exit rate of \(+2\%\) in North America given at the FY in June. US Specialty should continue to outperform at MSD% YoY rental growth, while US General Tool is likely to continue growing at LSD%, with continued solid growth from mega- projects, and persistent weakness in local construction markets. We expect an upward revision to FY26 FCF guidance, reflecting the recently reinstated \(100\%\) bonus depreciation under the OBBBA (note, peer United Rentals raised its FCF guidance in July on the same basis - see Angel Castillo's note here). Company- compiled consensus for 1Q stands at revenues of \(2,779m\) , EBITDA of \(1,289m\) , implying a margin of \(46.4\%\) and adj PBT of \(\) 557m\$

FY26 guidance: For FY26 (financial year- end April), Ashtead guides for group rental revenue growth of \(0.4\%\) , which assumes fairly modest rate growth and no inflection in local non- residential construction markets. Management pointed out at the FY25 results that supply- demand dynamics were improving in the market, which should support rates. Gross capex guide is set at \(1.8 - 2.2bn\) (including slightly lower gains on disposal at \~ \(475m\) ), leading to a buoyant FCF guidance of \(2 - 2.3bn\) . Overall, this guidance implies PBT broadly flat YoY at just over \(2.1bn\) , assuming depreciation of \(c.2.5bn\) and interest at \~ \(535 - 540m\) . Company- compiled consensus for FY26 stands at revenues of \(10,930m\) , EBITDA of \(5,104m\) ( \(46.7\%\) margin), EBITA of \(2,683m\) ( \(24.5\%\) margin), adj PBT of \(2,147m\) and diluted adj. EPS of \(376c\) .

Stay Overweight: We view Ashtead as a structural long- term growth play, a market leader in a consolidation story. We think an outsized share of mega- projects and an increasing shift toward rental vs owned equipment should see continued market share gains. Additionally, increased exposure to non- construction/specialty/MRO provides increasing protection from a cyclical downturn. While near- term growth is likely to be held back by ongoing uncertainty in US construction markets alongside high interest rates, we believe we are past the trough of the downgrade cycle and consensus looks well calibrated from here. Ashtead's Sunbelt 4.0 roadmap to 2029 targets a 5- year organic rental revenue CAGR of \(6 - 9\%\) for the US/Group, with volume growth from greenfields and same- store alongside rate progression driving a \~10% EPS CAGR to 2029.

We use a DCF- based valuation for Ashtead, and cross- reference that with historical average and peer multiples. Our DCF assumes an \(8.0\%\) WACC and \(3\%\) terminal growth rate.

- Recession/non-residential construction entering a cyclical downturn, resulting in fleet overcapacity and margin compression- Increasing competition for greenfield space or acquisition targets leading to a reduction in market share gains from consolidation
